definition.value: A member of the class of monofluorobenzenes that is benzene substituted by 5-amino-4-cyano-1H-imidazol-1-yl, fluoro, and morpholin-4-yl groups at positions 1, 3 and 4, respectively.

A member of the clas of purines that is 9H-purine substituted by 3,4-dimethoxyphenyl, aminocarbonyl, and 4-(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)-3-nitrophenyl groups at positions 2, 6 and 9, respectively. It is an inhibitor of EGFR and a potential anticancer agent.
The dihydrochloride salt of NNC 55-0396. It is a stable analogue of mibefradil and a highly selective T-type calcium channel blocker.

A synthetic alpha-L-rhamnoside consisting of a linear trisaccharide of beta-D-glucosyl, beta-D-glucosyl and 2-O-acetyl-alpha-L-rhamnosyl residues linked sequentially (1->6) and (1->3), to the beta-D-glucosyl residue are also linked alpha-L-rhamnosyl and N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residues via (1->3) and (1->6) linkages respectively. An aminoethyl linker from the reducing-end RhaNAc residue allows for efficient conjugation to a carrier protein.
A omega-hydroxy-fatty acid with a chain length ranging from C6 to C12.
A omega-hydroxy-fatty acid with a chain length ranging from C23 to C26.

A synthetic alpha-D-glucoside that is a branched decasaccharide derivative consisting of alpha-L-rhamnosyl, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl and alpha-D-glucosyl residues linked sequentially (1->3) and (1->4), to the alpha-D-glucosyl residue at the reducing end are also linked alpha-L-rhamnosyl and beta-D-glucosyl residues via (1->3) and (1->6) linkages respectively. An aminoethyl linker from the reducing-end Glc residue allows for efficient conjugation to a carrier protein.
A omega-hydroxy-fatty acid with a chain length of less than C6.
A guanidinium ion that is the conjugate acid of N-hydroxyguanidine, resulting from the protonation of the imine nitrogen; Major species at pH 7.3.
Major species at pH 7.3
Any halo fatty acid containing at least one chloro substituent.
A peptide anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-formyl-L-methionyl-L-leucyl-L-phenylalanine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-chloro-L-phenylalanine with the amino group of glycine.
An ortho-fused polycyclic arene, or derivative thereof, that consists of 9H-fluorene bearing an acetamido substituent at position 2.
Any monounsaturated fatty acid carrying one or more hydroperoxy substituents.
Any unsaturated fatty acid carrying one or more hydroperoxy substituents.

A polysaccharide derivative with a pentasaccharide repeat unit consisting of alpha-D-glucosyl, 2-O-acetyl-alpha-L-rhamnosyl and N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residues all linked (1->3), to the alpha-glucosyl residue of which are attached a beta-D-glucosyl residue and an alpha-L-rhamnosyl residue via (1->6) and (1->3) linkages respectively, with all repeat units being linked (1->4). The repeat unit corresponds to that of the native Escherichia coli serotype O25B O-antigen.
A peptide cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy terminus and protonation of the side-chain amino group and the amino terminus of Gly-Lys; major species at pH 7.3.
A composition-only glycan consisting of six hexosyl groups, seven acetaminohexosyl groups and two 6-deoxyhexosyl groups (identities and connectivity unknown). Composition: Hex6 HexNAc7 dHex2.
Antibiotic produced by some fungi.
The 5beta-stereoisomer of bufol.
Polymeric sulfated hyaluronan, degree of sulfation 1.2
Polymeric sulfated hyaluronan, degree of sulfation 3.5
Trideca-sulfo-hyaluronan-hexasaccharide, degree of sulfation 4.3
A steroid sulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 25-hydroxyvitamin D3 sulfate, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any agent that interferes with the activity of T-type calcium channels.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of {4-[1-(trifluoromethyl)cyclopropyl]phenyl}acetic acid with the amino group of 6-[(3-amino-1H-pyrazol-1-yl)methyl]pyridine-3-carbonitrile. It is a selective, orally available T-type calcium channel blocker that is being studied as a potential new treatment in epilepsy.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteinate that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-S-benzyl-L-cysteine resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteinate that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-S-hydroxy-L-cysteine resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricyclic diterpenoid with formula C20H32O2.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteinate that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-S-methyl-L-cysteine resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricyclic diterpenoid with formula C20H32O3. It is produced by the bird's nest fungus Cyathus earlei.
